# Paths excluded from the distribution tarball produced by release.yml.
# These exist in the template repo for the GAIA team's own workflow but have
# no business on an adopter's machine. Format is tar --exclude-from: one
# path or glob per line, comments with `#` are honored.
#
# Anything excluded here is ALSO skipped by `gaia-maintainer release manifest`, so the
# adopter-facing manifest never references files an adopter cannot have.
# Authoritative narrative of what's maintainer-only and why lives in
# `wiki/concepts/Release Workflow.md` (Distribution Boundary section).
#
# Categories below are ordered the same way that page lists them.

# --- 1. Maintainer-only Claude surface ---
# /gaia-release cuts releases of the GAIA template itself; adopters never
# release GAIA. The release-notes skill translates GAIA's CHANGELOG into
# public release notes for the marketing site, a release-time maintainer
# task, so it ships nowhere just like /gaia-release. /health-audit is the
# maintainer-only autonomous audit + auto-heal loop (runbook lives under
# .gaia/cli/health/, already excluded wholesale via category 10). Other
# /gaia-* commands (plan, handoff, pickup, audit) are adopter-useful and
# must NOT be added here. preferred-base.sh is the maintainer's personal
# statusline left-side renderer; adopters get the right-side-only
# gaia-statusline.sh wrapper which delegates left-side rendering to the
# user's own global statusline. The three code-audit-maintainer-* agents are
# the Code Audit Team's maintainer-only members (framework shell + framework
# TypeScript + skills-prose lenses); adopters audit only their own app via
# code-audit-frontend. /distribution-audit is the maintainer's
# ship-or-withhold audit over newly-shipping files; it drives the
# maintainer-only release CLI and has no meaning on an adopter clone.
.claude/commands/gaia-release.md
.claude/commands/health-audit.md
.claude/skills/release-notes
.gaia/statusline/preferred-base.sh
.claude/agents/code-audit-maintainer-shell.md
.claude/agents/code-audit-maintainer-node.md
.claude/agents/code-audit-maintainer-prose.md
.claude/commands/distribution-audit.md
# Maintainer-only Code Audit Team spawn-list optimization; adopters resolve required members via resolve-audit-members.sh and the frontend self-skip is fail-closed on its absence.
.gaia/scripts/resolve-audit-spawn.sh
# verify-required-checks.sh declares the required_status_checks the GAIA team's own
# branch ruleset must enforce (job names like "bats (.github/audit)" that only exist
# on maintainer-only, release-excluded workflows); an adopter clone has no such
# ruleset and none of those jobs, so the script has no adopter surface.
.gaia/scripts/verify-required-checks.sh

# --- 2. Maintainer-only wiki content ---
# Internal vault administration files and team-specific knowledge that
# describes the GAIA project itself rather than reusable patterns.
wiki/entities
wiki/meta
wiki/.obsidian/workspace.json
wiki/concepts/Release Workflow.md
wiki/concepts/Release-Notes.md
wiki/decisions/Bundle-time Scrub.md
wiki/decisions/CLI-Binary-Split.md
wiki/decisions/Forensics Triage Workflow.md

# --- 3. Test harnesses and audit reports ---
# Smoke / observability harnesses run by maintainers in CI; never invoked
# from an adopter's project. .claude/rules/maintainers/ holds maintainer-only
# rules (smoke-harness conventions plus other maintainer-only guidance) that
# must never ship to an adopter.
# .gaia/scripts/tests and .github/audit/tests are bats suites for shipped
# GAIA-owned scripts (.gaia/scripts/ and .github/audit/ helpers). Their only
# runner, audit-ci-tests.yml, is release-excluded (category 9), so they never
# execute on an adopter clone; adopters receive the verified scripts as owned
# code they never edit, so the suites guard only maintainer changes.
.gaia/tests
.gaia/scripts/tests
.claude/rules/maintainers
.github/audit/tests
.specify/extensions/gaia/test
# react-perf-smoke.spec.ts is the bippy version-bump canary: it asserts GAIA's
# capture harness still resolves a known GAIA component (ThemeSwitch) by name +
# memo + timing, and that the StrictMode bypass fires. It guards GAIA's own
# instrumentation against a bippy/React upgrade, not adopter app behavior, and
# is coupled to a GAIA component an adopter may rename or remove. The capture
# helper it exercises (.playwright/react-perf/) DOES ship; this canary does not.
.playwright/e2e/react-perf-smoke.spec.ts

# --- 4. CLI maintainer source + maintainer binary ---
# Adopters receive only the bundled adopter binary at .gaia/cli/gaia (and
# the templates at .gaia/cli/templates/). Source, tests, fixtures, and
# build configs stay in the template repo so adopters can't accidentally
# rebuild the binary out from under themselves.
#
# .gaia/cli/gaia-maintainer is the second bundle produced by `pnpm bundle`
# (entry: src/index.maintainer.ts). It carries the maintainer-only
# `release` namespace and exists only on the GAIA team's clone; adopters
# never see it. The adopter `gaia` binary's source (src/index.ts) does not
# import any release code, so esbuild keeps the release surface out of the
# adopter bundle by construction.
.gaia/cli/src
.gaia/cli/test-fixtures
.gaia/cli/package.json
.gaia/cli/pnpm-lock.yaml
.gaia/cli/pnpm-workspace.yaml
.gaia/cli/tsconfig.json
.gaia/cli/vitest.config.ts
.gaia/cli/eslint.config.mjs
.gaia/cli/prettier.config.mjs
.gaia/cli/.gitignore
.gaia/cli/node_modules
.gaia/cli/dist
.gaia/cli/gaia-maintainer

# --- 5. Release-time maintainer tooling ---
# This file itself: adopters don't run GAIA releases. The release-scrub
# config drives `gaia-maintainer release scrub` (bundle-time marker-strip + leak-check)
# and is consumed only by the maintainer's release.yml. Note:
# `.gaia/scripts/` DOES ship: `check-updates.sh` is the background refresher
# invoked by the adopter-facing statusline (writes the cache the statusline
# reads for `Run /update-deps` and `Run /update-gaia` indicators).
.gaia/release-exclude
.gaia/release-scrub.yml

# --- 6. Maintainer dev-tool configs ---
# Per-machine tool configs initialized by `/setup-gaia` on the adopter's
# side; the template's copies aren't portable. Keep these out of the
# manifest so /update-gaia never tries to merge them.
.serena

# --- 7. Scratch + transient ---
# Local working directories: scratchpad ingestion, per-machine state
# (including the shared update-tarball cache at `.gaia/local/cache/shared/`),
# update-merge stage area, init backup. Per-machine SPEC state (the ledger at
# `.gaia/local/specs/ledger.json` plus the SPEC folders) lives under
# `.gaia/local/`, already excluded by the line below; a fresh adopter starts
# SPEC numbering from an empty local ledger and an unseeded remote `spec/*`
# tag namespace.
.raw
.gaia/local
.gaia-backup
.gaia-merge

# --- 8. Per-machine plan / handoff / agent state ---
# Generated at runtime under the user's clone; not template content.
.claude/worktrees
.claude/agent-memory

# --- 9. Maintainer-only CI workflows ---
# `release.yml` cuts releases of the GAIA template itself (triggered by
# `v*.*.*` tags); adopters never release GAIA. `cli-tests.yml` runs the
# .gaia/cli/ vitest suite; adopters receive only the bundled binary, so
# the test workflow has nothing to test on their side.
# `audit-ci-tests.yml` runs the bats suite for
# `.github/audit/check-trailer.sh`; adopters receive that script as
# GAIA-controlled code they never edit, so the suite guards only
# maintainer changes. `distribution.yml`
# runs the maintainer-only `.gaia/tests/distribution/` harness against a
# staged release tree using a Claude OAuth org secret; adopters never
# distribute GAIA. `forensics-triage.yml` runs autonomous Claude Code
# triage against `gaia-forensics`-labeled issues on the upstream
# `gaia-react/gaia` repo; the workflow's helpers under `.github/forensics/`
# include scope checks, classifier prompts, fixtures, and bats tests that
# only matter on the maintainer's clone. `code-review-audit.yml` installs
# on demand via `/setup-gaia` (like the cron workflows) rather than
# shipping by default, so adopters who have not enabled GAIA CI never carry
# a credential-less audit that blocks every merge. `shell-lint.yml` runs
# shellcheck over GAIA's framework bash via the `.gaia/tests/shell-lint.sh`
# harness (already excluded by the `.gaia/tests` entry in category 3); adopters
# run that bash but never author it, so the linter guarding it has no adopter
# surface. `distribution-audit-pr.yml` fails a PR that introduces a
# newly-shipping file the committed manifest does not answer, by running the
# maintainer-only `gaia-maintainer release manifest --check`; the binary and the
# manifest exist only on the GAIA team's clone, so the gate has no adopter
# surface. `verify-required-checks.yml` (#807) runs the maintainer-only
# .gaia/scripts/verify-required-checks.sh advisory drift check against the
# GAIA team's own branch ruleset; an adopter clone has neither that ruleset
# nor the script it depends on (already excluded, category 1). All would be
# silent passengers at best and confusing CI failures at worst on adopter
# clones.
.github/workflows/release.yml
.github/workflows/cli-tests.yml
.github/workflows/audit-ci-tests.yml
.github/workflows/distribution.yml
.github/workflows/forensics-triage.yml
.github/workflows/code-review-audit.yml
.github/workflows/shell-lint.yml
.github/workflows/distribution-audit-pr.yml
.github/workflows/verify-required-checks.yml
# `audit-roster.yml` runs the maintainer-only .gaia/scripts/verify-audit-roster.sh
# advisory drift check against the GAIA team's own Code Audit Team roster
# (.gaia/audit-ci.yml) and machinery lists; an adopter clone's own roster is
# adopter-owned and this script's invariants are a maintainer-repo concern,
# so the check would be a silent passenger on adopter clones.
.github/workflows/audit-roster.yml
.github/forensics

# --- 10. Maintainer-only health-audit infrastructure ---
# `.gaia/cli/health/` holds the audit taxonomy, run state, and (post-#97)
# the orchestrator's per-cycle outputs. Only maintainers run health audits
# against the GAIA template; adopters audit their own app via the standard
# `code-review-audit` agent. The bundled `gaia` binary does not import
# from `src/health/`, so esbuild tree-shakes any future health code out
# of the adopter binary by construction.
.gaia/cli/health
.gaia/cli/src/health

# --- 11. Maintainer-only project governance ---
# Adopters use GAIA as a template via `npx create-gaia` and run independent
# projects with their own license, contributors, changelog, README, and
# code-of-conduct decisions. Shipping GAIA's copies makes their project
# inherit GAIA-the-template's governance, wrong by default. The README
# is regenerated by `/gaia-init` from `.gaia/templates/README.md` (which
# DOES ship); the others are adopter responsibility. CODEOWNERS encodes
# who owns code review on the GAIA repo; an adopter's owners are their own,
# so `/gaia-init` writes a fresh `.github/CODEOWNERS` (`* @<their-username>`)
# during setup rather than inheriting GAIA's.
.github/CODEOWNERS
CHANGELOG.md
CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md
CONTRIBUTING.md
LICENSE
README.md
SUPPORTERS.md

